ri: Structure and Style of Chariton’s Novel -- tNew Evidence For Dating The Discovery At Traù Of The Petronian Cena Trimalchionis -- tBologna as Hypata: Annotation, Transformation, and Transl(oc)ation in the Circles of Filippo Beroaldo and Francesco Colonna -- tThe First Japanese Translation of Daphnis & Chloe -- tBoundaries: Geographical and Metaphorical -- tRefiguring the Animal/Human Divide in Apuleius and Heliodorus -- tEros the Cheese Maker: A Food Studies Approach to Daphnis and Chloe -- tRethinking Landscape in Ancient Fiction: Mountains in Apuleius and Jerome -- tKangaroo Courts: Displaced Justice in the Roman Novel -- tCharacter and Emotion in the Ancient Novel -- tPity vs. Forgiveness in Pagan and Judaeo-Christian Narratives -- tThe Interaction of Emotions in the Greek Novels -- tA Critique of Curiosity: Magic and Fiction in Apuleius’ Metamorphoses -- tSpectacles of a Dormant Soul: A Reading of Plato’s Gyges and Apuleius’ Lucius -- tWhy doesn’t Habrocomes run away from Aegialeus and his Mummified Wife?: Horror and the Ancient Novel -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex nominum et rerum -- tIndex locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe protagonists of the ancient novels wandered or were carried off to distant lands, from Italy in the west to Persia in the east and Ethiopia in the south; the authors themselves came, or pretended to come, from remote places such as Aphrodisia and Phoenicia; and the novelistic form had antecedents in a host of classical genres. These intersections are explored in this volume. Papers in the first section discuss “mapping the world in the novels.” The second part looks at the dialogical imagination, and the conversation between fiction and history in the novels. Section 3 looks at the way ancient fiction has been transmitted and received. Space, as the locus of cultural interaction and exchange, is the topic of the fourth part. The fifth and final section is devoted to character and emotion, and how these are perceived or constructed in ancient fiction. Overall, a rich picture is offered of the many spatial and cultural dimensions in a variety of ancient fictional genres.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aClassical fictionxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aCulture in literaturevCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient novel.  across-cultural.  afiction.  aspace.1 aBaker, Ashli Jane Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlood, H. Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodel, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, Shannon N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapra, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarver, Robert H. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnors, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCueva, Edmund P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinkelpearl, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFutre Pinheiro, Marília P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGómez, Pilar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaeger, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensson, Gottskálk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasprzyk, Dimitri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenaan, Vered Lev, econtributor